    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize if the analogies were a bit too...goblin-centric.\n\nTo troubleshoot the issue, let's focus on the technical aspects. A C-wire (common wire) issue is a possibility, as it provides power to the thermostat. If the C-wire is loose or not connected properly, it can cause the thermostat to malfunction.\n\nTo check the C-wire, you'll need to locate the wires connected to the thermostat. Typically, the C-wire is a thin, white or gray wire that's connected to the thermostat's power terminal. Check the wire's connection to the thermostat and the furnace. If the connection is loose, try tightening it.\n\nAs for checking the voltage, you can use a multimeter to measure the voltage at the thermostat and the furnace. Set the multimeter to DC voltage (20V) and touch the leads to the thermostat's power terminal and the furnace's power terminal. Take a reading to see if the voltage is dropping or fluctuating at night.\n\nKeep in mind that you should be careful when working with electrical systems, and if you're not comfortable with DIY troubleshooting, it's always best to consult a professional electrician or a Nest support specialist.",
